      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the world of real estate, much like a labyrinth of ancient ruins, can be quite bewildering, especially when you first step into it. Now, imagine you're a brave adventurer, and the house you're eyeing in Toronto is a treasure chest. But before you can claim your treasure, you must first pass through the enchanted forest of Escrow.\n\nAn escrow account is like a magical vault, guarded by a wise old goblin who ensures that all the gold coins (or in this case, money) are safely stored until the treasure chest (the house) is finally yours. This goblin, known as the escrow agent, makes sure that the buyer and seller both fulfill their promises before the treasure is handed over. It's a way to protect both parties from the mischievous goblins of deceit and fraud that might try to snatch the treasure away.\n\nSo, in the closing process, the escrow account acts as a neutral ground, a place where all the necessary spells (documents) are cast and the final incantations (payments) are made. Only when the goblin is satisfied that all the conditions have been met, does he release the treasure, allowing you to claim your new home in Toronto. And remember, adventurer",
